values:
I've been back at home for almost 7 months now, and I've been really bad about keeping in touch with people back at New College.  Some people have been contacting me about my bad-friendliness, and now I feel like I need to get back in contact with my college roots.  

I miss New College in that I miss having access to a lot of cool people in very close proximity.  At home, most of my friends are away at college or live really far south in Chicago, so I don't have a ton of social interaction.  School is a million times easier at the little state school that is basically just a step above community college, but now I'm working a real part-time job as a bank teller, so that kind of monopolizes my time.  I like it a lot, but it's definitely not something I want to do for the rest of my life, mostly due to the fact that the pay is crap.  I really just want to finish college, but they're making me take all these gen eds and minor classes that are going to delay me for a while.  It's better than going back to New College, paying 7+ times as much per semester, and having to write a thesis plus do 3 ISPs, though.

I just want to get a cushy job so that I can take vacations to see everyone around the country whom I've lost touch with, pay off my student loans and move out of my parents' house.

Speaking of my parents' house, they're still not done with construction so we're still living in an apartment.  I didn't mind it at first, but now I'm so incredibly sick of this place.  I also really miss being somewhat independent back in Sarasota.  I really enjoyed living away from home, and I probably won't be doing it again until it's financially responsible for me to do so.  That won't be for some time.  I really hope I'm not 30 and still living at home.

Anyway, that's the end of my rambling.  I think I'm going to try to visit Sarasota next semester, so whoever will still be around and would like to see me should be prepared.  And someone should offer me their floor.

Look at your LJ "interests" list. If you have fewer than 50 interests, pick every fifth one. If you have between fifty and seventy-five interests, pick every seventh one. If you have over seventy-five interests, pick every tenth one. If you have fewer than ten, pick all of 'em. List them here, and tell everyone exactly what it is about these things that interests you so much. accents: I like my Chicago twang. I like speaking in accents that are not my own. I like when people use accents different from my own, whether they are real or not. Basically, I like everything about accents. Annie Hall: I first saw Annie Hall about a year and a half ago at a friend's house, and I laughed out loud at almost every single joke. I have yet to see it or any other Woody Allen movie again, but I enjoyed that one time thoroughly. Battle of Algiers: This is simply an amazing film. It was commissioned by the Algerian government to show both sides of the Algerian revolution. The film itself definitely has more sympathy for the Algerians, but it portrays the French in a mostly positive light. It looks like a documentary, but everything was scripted, based on true events. If this isn't my absolute favorite movie ever, it's pretty close. card playing: I liked playing cards long before I went to Baton Rouge, but the summer made it an obsession. Now, if anyone ever asks me to play a card game I like (including but not limited to euchre, setback, spades, sheepshead, asshole, crazy eights, klabberjass, gin, bridge, canasta, cribbage, Phase 10, war, Set, blitz, Uno...), I will play immediately with no regard to what I'd been doing previously. Moreover, card games will forever remind me of Michelle, Anthony, Nee, Rachel, Daniel and all the others, and at very least for this reason, they will always have a special place in my heart. diesel sweeties: I was really into a few online comics for a while, and this was one of them. It's about the future where robots and humans mix freely and have inter-whatever relationships. It's " indie ". I dunno. I think it's gotten progressively worse since Maura and Clango broke up. I still read it a few times a week, but not every day. It's located here. French: When it came time for me to pick a language in high school, I really wanted to take Italian, but my school didn't offer it. So I decided to take Japanese or Chinese, but neither worked with my schedule. French seemed like a better choice than Spanish, German or Latin. I'm really glad that I ended up taking it and that I'm taking it again now. I think the inherent snottiness is part of the charm. I always feel like I'm in some elite club when I'm speaking French. Harvey Pekar: I first found out about Harvey from watching American Splendor (which is also awesome). He was a record and comics junkie, working as a file clerk, when he got fed up and started writing comics about his everyday life. His friend, R. Crumb (a noted underground comic artist), offered to do the graphics for his comics. Pretty quickly, Harvey became an underground comic god. Since seeing the movie, I've read some of his books and found them funny and relatable. Everyone should check out his stuff/American Splendor. Karaoke Revolution: This game is so fun. It's like Dance Dance Revolution, except for singing. I'm pretty good, which makes it even better. The only problem is that there are only like 35 songs per version of the game, so you run through them pretty fast. Regardless, it's awesome. Monkeys: This is a movie some guys from my high school made for a film class. It's about space monkeys that are trying to gain world domination by taking over people's bodies and then destroying stuff. It's better than it sounds. The sequel, Monkeys 2, is even better (the image above is from Monkeys 2). They're both available for purchase here. Nino Quincampoix: Nino is the guy Amelie falls for in her movie. I'm kinda over Jeunet's cutesy, overprecious direction and the immense popularity of the film among people who think they're artsy because they like Amelie, but I never get sick of Nino (or Amelie herself, for that matter). proofs:Being able to prove stuff is definitely true (based on axioms) is the best part of doing math. I couldn't give less of a crap about numbers or functions or any of that stuff. Doing proofs is where it's at. Rilo Kiley: Kate introduced me to Rilo Kiley about two or three years ago. They make melodic, poppy music. I like them, but not as much as some other people I know. Their first album is a lot better than the third but not as good as the second. I wish they'd mix it up more and try new things. But Blake was in the Nickelodeon classic show "Salute Your Shorts"! shoulder rests: I played the viola for about 10 years, but I've touched it once since coming to college, when I broke a string trying to tune it. I don't know if I could even play the viola without a shoulder rest anymore. It makes it infinitely more comfortable and helps you hold the neck up. Yep. The Cubs: Being from Chicago and especially being from my family, baseball is very important to me. I really get caught up in the Cubs; each game seems extremely important, even in the beginning of the season. I'm not completely convinced that they're out of this season's playoffs yet, even though they're 5.5 games back in the wild card race with only twenty games left, which means that if the sum of the number of their losses and the Astros wins reaches 15, they're eliminated. They've still got seven games with the Astros, so anything could happen, although there are 3 teams in between them and Houston. Twelve Angry Men: If you don't know why this movie is awesome, go rent it right now. (the Henry Fonda version, not the '90s one!) Yves Montand: He was a French actor who did a bunch of French movies. He was also in a few English language movies, but none of this is why I know him. He has a song on the Rushmore soundtrack, and on a whim one day, I downloaded all the music from him that I could find. He's a less masculine Frank Sinatra who sings in French. I like 'im a lot. The end. Do the meme; it's fun, especially with pictures!

Your brain: 80% interpersonal, 40% visual, 140% verbal, and 140% mathematical!
Congratulations on being 400% smart! Actually, on my test, everyone is. The above score breaks down what kind of thinking you most enjoy doing. A score above 100% means you use that kind of thinking more than average, and a score below 100% means you use it less. It says nothing about how good you are at any one, just how interested you are in each, relatively. A substantial difference in scores between two people means, conclusively, that they are different kinds of thinkers.

Matching Summary: Each of us has different tastes. Still, I offer the following advice, which I think is obvious:

  1. Don't date someone if your interpersonal percentages differ by more than 80%.
  2. Don't be friends with someone if your verbal percentages differ by more than 100%.
  3. Don't have sex with someone if their math percentage is over 200%.

by popular demand... I hate it, but I think that has a lot to do with the fact that I looooved my last haircut. I dunno, it'll probably end up being ok, but right now, I want to rewind time 9 hours. I feel too lazy to post more. I'm going to be posting daily in a Louisiana blog starting Sunday, but I won't give you the link right now, because it's not ready. I never thought I'd be so bummed about a haircut.

I feel a lot better today. The chest congestion seems to have gotten worse, but the cough is increasingly less frequent and as such, my throat doesn't hurt as much. Luckily for me, what makes me most noticeably sick right now is my voice. When I start talking, I sound mostly fine, maybe a little sick, but then after about 5 seconds, it suddenly drops out completely and I'm whispering. It's pretty fun, so I've been sitting here for about 10 minutes saying things like "When is going to drop out? When is going to drop out? There it goes.. Sometimes I get that low grumbly voice that is characteristic of sick people too. I'm amused by the constant changes, and if you've got the time, you should take a chance to witness it. I didn't get much work done last night, and I went back to sleep after turning my alarm off at 6 am. Really, I should be over in the fishbowl again working on my music theory projects, but I'm still waking up, and the piano will still be there in 10 minutes. Now that my sick story is believable (because it was true), I really need to finish those projects so that I have something to show him today.

You Are 24 Years Old

Under 12: You are a kid at heart. You still have an optimistic life view - and you look at the world with awe. 13-19: You are a teenager at heart. What Age Do You Act?
You Know You're From Chicago When...
You say "Wanna go with?" when you mean "Do you want to come with me?" You know what Kennedy, Dan Ryan, Eisenhower, Edens, and Bishop Ford, have in common and curse one of them daily. You know what "the Hillside strangler is." You can name three or four extra taxes nobody else pays. You know the difference between Richard J Daley and Richard M Daley. You can use two or three Daleyisms in context. You can imitate the Mayor's whine. You say Chicawgo and not Chicaago. You think going to a Bears game in single digit temperatures with a wind off the lake (and freezing rain) is fun. Da is a proper definite article. You expect corruption in local politics. You go to the Dells in the summer to get away from the other 20 thousand that followed you. You've been caught speeding in Wisconsin because you had Illinois plates. You guard your shoveled parking space with an old chair and unusable broom. You know why they call it "the Windy City." You know dead people who voted. You understand the Democratic machine and don't fight against it. You've never ever considered the idea of hiring non-union laborers. You've never been to Springfield. You know a good gyros joint. You know what Giordanos, Lou Malnati's, and Gino's have in common. You know when the last time the Cubs won a pennant. You know exactly how many cars are "legally" allowed to turn left after the light turns red. You don't know which ethnic "fest" to choose on any given Summer weekend. Your idea of relaxing and getting away from it all is Ravinia (with 10,000 others who have the same idea). You can recite many of "The Blues Brothers" lines and know where they filmed certain scenes. You consider paying someone to watch your car at a sporting event as just another "city tax." The "Living Room" is called the "front room" You don't pronounce the "s" at the end of Illinois. You become irate at people who do You measure distance in minutes (especially "from the city"). And you swear everything is pretty much 15 minutes away You refer to anything South of I-80 as "Southern Illinois" You refer to Lake Michigan as "The Lake" You refer to Chicago as "The City" "The Super Bowl" refers to one specific game in a series of 35 played in January of 1986 You have two favorite football teams: The Bears, and anyone who beats the Packers! You buy "The Trib" You think 35 degrees is great weather to wash your car! You know what goes on a Chicago Style Hot Dog You know what Chicago Style Pizza REALLY is You understand what "lake-effect" means You know the difference between Amtrak and Metra, and know which station they end up at. You have ridden the "L" You can distinguish between the following area codes: 847,630,773,708, 312, & 815 You respond to the question "Where are you from" with a side" example:"WEST SIDE", "SOUTH SIDE" or "NORTHSIDE." You know what the phone number is to Empire Carpet! You wear gym shoes, not sneakers. Your favorite melody to hum is "Bang,Bang,Bang-Skeet,Skeet,Skeet!!!!" You faithfully attended Lil Louis parties at The Bismarck. You GOT to have spaghetti at your barbecue. You are STILL a Bulls fan........ You think kicking it outside of White Castles parking lot, (79th and Stony Island) is the "Freak Nik" You go to Harold`s and order 4 pc wing, mild sauce, salt and pepper. You have a picture of Harold Washington in your kitchen, living room, family room or basement. You have ever waited in line at Home of the Hoagy on 111th for 30-45 minutes for a steak samich wit cheese You have ever been to the Tiki Room lounge in Hyde Park You have Y made a special trip downtown because you had a craving for Garrett's caramel and cheese popcorn. What!!! We don`t get a Fifty? Oh yeah.... You drink at bars called "Bud on Tap" or "Milwaukee's Best" -- no names, just beer signs out front. It's January and you see someone's kitchen chair in the street, and you know that if you're a responsible citizen and bring it back to the sidewalk you will be shot on sight You live two miles from work and it takes you two hours to drive there You don't flinch when you pay the fifth toll of your 45-minute car ride on the highway When you read a big story in the paper about mob ties in the city government, your first reaction is "So, tell me something I don't know." You know Lincoln Towing is Satan incarnate. You've paid $105 for towing, $30 for more than one "street cleaning" ticket, $58 for a city vehicle sticker, and $70 for a license plate sticker -- and chalk it all up to "neighborhood taxes." You pluralize grocery stores and retail chains: "I'm going to Jewels"; "I bought it at Targets"; "I couldn't find parking at Wal-Marts" You've taken the Red Line past the point where all white people get off and all black people get on -- or vice versa. You've cursed at a cyclist, pedestrian, or in-line skater on the lakefront path. You know the significance of State and Madison. You wonder if the fries will taste the same at Sammy Sosa's Restaurant. You don't miss Planet Hollywood. You're not ashamed of wearing a big fur Russian hat, or a headsock with one hole in it, in public from November through March. You actually get these jokes and pass them on to other friends from Chicago.

I slept until noon today.  This is insanely late for me.  I think the latest I've ever slept before was probably 10:15-ish.  Unfortunately, I had class at 12:30, and I proceeded to lock myself out while getting ready, before grabbing shoes and my bag.  I ended up being 20 minutes late to class.  

It's been a really frustrating couple of days.  I want to go home, where I don't have any responsibilities.
Three reasons to go here and help save my favorite television show: 1. Robots and monsters. 2. Bible lessons. 3. HOT COPS.

I am finally back.

Travelling is stressful.

I got me a haircut and bought some new makeup. I was really worried about it because she just kept cutting and she blow dried it really messily in the beginning, but it came out well. I'm a little anxious about how it'll look tomorrow when I just take a shower and leave it to air dry, but if it's really bad, I guess I'll just have to start blow drying it myself. In other news, my break has been good, but not very productive. I had an urge to go back to school today, but I'm glad that I'm staying until Sunday. Hopefully, I will get more productive and actually catch up with my homework, like I had planned.

I accepted the LSU REU.  After hearing a bunch of maybes and "can't tell you right now"s, I decided that the safest option was the best.  The fact that I started getting super excited right after I decided to take it makes me feel that I made the right decision.  Here's to hoping that I'm not too dumb for this and that the projects aren't boring!

"We are pleased to invite you to participate in our Research 
Experiences for Undergraduates Program at Louisiana State University 
for the summer of 2005. You will receive a stipend of $2,500, payable 
in installments. In addition, you will be provided accommodations in 
LSU campus housing and you will be eligible for reimbursement of 
actual travel expenses up to $350. This funding is provided through a 
grant from the National Science Foundation entitled ``Mathematical 
Research Experiences for Undergraduate Program at Louisiana State 
University." Your responsibility will be to participate fully in the 
activities of the program, including the preparation of a paper 
describing your research activities in the program, to be written 
during the final weeks of the program.

  The program is scheduled to begin Monday, 6 June and continue
through Friday, 29 July.

 Please let us know by return email that you have received this offer 
and then inform us of your acceptance or declination of this offer by 
noon Thursday, 10 March at the latest. If you have any further 
questions, please feel free to contact us (and check our REU web page 
http://www.math.lsu.edu/REU/). We look forward to having you in our 
program.

Cordially,

Neal W. Stoltzfus
Robert Perlis
William Hoffman"

So, yay, I have an option, but boo, they want me to reply by Thursday.  I haven't even gotten a yes or no from anybody else and may not get anything until after Thursday.  I just think it's unreasonable for them to ask me to decide this quickly.  I'm sure that they want to be able to fill the places of people who decline before other REUs grab them up, but I dunwanna have to decide so soon.

Then again, the project (Toric Varieties, Ihara Zeta Functions of Graphs, Braids and Knot Theory) sounds fun.  I actually had assumed I wouldn't get this one, since I haven't had any topology and it seemed like you would need a little to do their program.  Otherwise, there aren't many pluses.  The stipend and other amenities are pretty much the standard for REUs, and LSU isn't exactly known as a pillar of knowledge.  I just wish Eirini would get back to me and make this decision at least a little easier.

I am tired.  Early bed time tonight, methinks.

My dad's talking about getting me a car for next year again.  I don't want to get my hopes up again, but I think that it's more plausible this year because I will have money (current refund check, prospective stipend from REU) to pay for insurance.  It would have to be nice enough to get me from Chicago to Sarasota, since that's one of the things he's proposing.  And it'd be super duper awesome to have a car for concerts, possible Disney trips and other nonboredom.  

Ok, so maybe I am getting my hopes up.

In other news, I just helped choose the orientation planner and RA selection committee.  Dan Sarkissian will be the former and the latter is now composed of Paolo, Adesh, Kristin Psiaki, Shannon Benge and Brian Ellison, in case you were wondering.  I really enjoyed the meetings, especially the RA selection.  I didn't think that I was going to run for some NCSA position for next year, but I really do enjoy being involved, so I'm reconsidering.  I barely ever say anything at meetings, but I feel that I would say more if the "Residence Life Rep" had more responsibilities.  Or any responsibilities.

In any case, I'm in a good mood, despite the fact that I did almost none of the things I wanted to do this weekend.  Fun meetings and 2 new Arrested Development episodes starting in about 10 minutes, woo hoo!

P.S. Charissa, I am seriously addicted to buffalo wings now.  It's been less than two days since I last had them, and already I am craving them again.  Grrrrrrrrrrrrrrr to you, Charz!

I just came from what was most likely my first failed math exam ever.  I feel like shit.  Whenever I do worse than I should have on a math test, I really question whether or not I should be devoting my life to this stuff.  I know it's not really reasonable, since I missed the class where he talked about the things I didn't get (which was like half the exam), and that I haven't been keeping up with my work, studying hard enough, going to him with questions, etc.  The exam wasn't bad.  I felt relatively prepared.  But I wasn't, at all, really.  I feel like I'm doomed to repeat this ad infinitum.  It happened last semester with Calc III, and it feels like it will continue to happen now.

I don't know.  I feel really dumb right now.  I'm in the library, avoiding my room because it symbolizes applications and homework and grading that has to be finished, and I want to avoid anything like math for as long as possible, right now.

Movie Meme: 1. Pick a dozen movies that are ones that you have special feelings about. 2. Pick a few lines of dialogue that mean something to you. 3. As people guess the film, strike out that entry. 4. If possible, after the film is guessed, explain why that movie. 1. There's an old joke. Uh, two elderly women are at a Catskills mountain resort, and one of 'em says, "Boy, the food at this place is really terrible." The other one says, "Yeah, I know, and such small portions." Well, that's essentially how I feel about life. Full of loneliness and misery and suffering and unhappiness, and it's all over much too quickly. 2. All right, all right, don't lose your blob! 3. Paul Power... Paul for President... Paul... Promise... Progress... Peanut... 4."Look, I know that sometimes I let him get away with..." "EVERYTHING!" 5. "Have you no morals, man?" "Nah. Can't afford none. Neither could you, if you were as poor as me." 6. "Have you lost your mind? You're just a child!" "I smoke, I snort, I've killed and robbed. I'm a man." 7. What we were after now was the old surprise visit. That was a real kick and good for laughs and lashings of the old ultraviolence. 8. "Hey listen, if you guys do something later, can I join you?" "We're not gonna do something." "No, I know, but if you do, can I join you?" "We're not gonna do something later." "Okay, but, if you do?" "Okay." "Cool." 9. "Richie, this illness, this closeness to death... it's had a profound affect on me. I feel like a different person, I really do." "Dad, you were never dying." "But I'm gonna live." 10. "I beg pardon..." " 'I beg pardon?' What are you so polite about?" "For the same reason you are not: it's the way I was brought up."

<lj-cut text="calc evaluation">
 This course was a solid introduction to vector calculus. The text for
the course was "Calculus: Early Transcendentals," Fifth Edition, by
James Stewart. The course covered chapters 12-16 of the text. This
included an introduction to vectors and the geometry of space (dot
products, vector products, lines, planes, cylinders and quadric
surfaces), vector valued functions, the standard material concerning
partial derivatives (including tangent plane approximations, the chain
rule, max/min problems and Lagrange multipliers), multiple integrals,
vector fields, line integrals, curl, divergence, Green's Theorem,
surface integrals and the Divergence Theorem (hurricanes precluded
covering the material on Stokes' Theorem). The class met three times
per week for lecture and once per week for a voluntary problem
session. There were three in-class exams and weekly (roughly) homework
assignments. The evaluation is based on student exam performance.

Your homework performance for the semester was satisfactory.

Your performance on the first exam was strong and indicated a working
knowledge of all the material central to the course. In particular,
you did excellent work on the problem involving lines and planes, the
problem involving vector algebra, problem involving surfaces, curves
and tangent plane constructions, and the problem concerning partial
differentiation and Laplace's equation. Your work on the problem
involving limits and continuity for functions of several variables was
not as strong, but indicated no serious problems. All told, this was
a very good performance.

Your performance on the second exam, while marred by some small
computational mistakes, was solidly satisfactory. You did solid work
on the material involving classification of critical points and the
material involving Lagrange multipliers. Your work on double
integrals contained a number of computational errors, but it appears
that you know the material. Your work on triple integrals was mixed:
you were able to set up the required integrals in Euclidean and
cylindrical coordinates, but you had some trouble with spherical
coordinates and with changing the order of integration. All told,
this performance indicated that you were familiar with the main topics
being examined.

Your performance on the final exam was satisfactory. You did solid
work on the material involving the computation of divergence and curl
for given vector fields and the material involving the construction of
a potential for a given conservative field. You correctly stated and
applied Green's Theorem. You made a serious computational error on
the problem involving line integrals. While you were able to
correctly state the Divergence Theorem, you had trouble applying it
(the surface integral seems to have given you trouble). All told,
your performance indicated mastery of the core material of the
semester, save the computation of surface integrals.

Given the above, I find your performance for the semester to be
clearly satisfactory. I encourage you to continue your studies of
mathematics and I look forward to working more with you in the future.

So, I passed my calc test. Pat said that the scores were mostly in the 43%-78% range and passing was 50%, and I got a 74%. I'm happy, because I basically crammed 7 weeks of learning into three and a half hours, but I still have a lot of regret about how seriously I've taken that class this mod. There's really no excuse for it. The material didn't get much more difficult. I may have started the mod with more work than I knew what to do with, but that changed as the weeks went by. I'm really frustrated with myself right now. I feel like I'm lapsing back into my high school habits, and that's definitely undesirable. I wish I would just be diligent with my work, no matter how boring. It is very important for me to not only pass the calculus and pass it with flying colors, but also to impress Pat. I've been writing my evaluation in my head, and it's just not very good. And it's all my fault. Sure, the overabundance of physics problems he does in class bore me to tears. Sure, the homework tends to be monotonous. But it still must be done. So this weekend, I'm going to do all the assignments I haven't formally done and turn them in on Monday to the TA's box or something. I don't know if it will help the homework portion of my evaluation, since some of it will be extremely late, but it'll make me feel better about my level of commitment to the class and it will help insure that I understand the material. Done and done.
